# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: astro
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro components are extremely flexible.
[src:astro/astro-components] An Astro component can be as small as a snippet of HTML, like a collection of common `<meta>` tags that make SEO easy to work with.
[src:astro/astro-components] Components can be reusable UI elements, like a header or a profile card.
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro components can even contain an entire page layout or, when located in the special `src/pages/` folder, be an entire page itself.
[src:astro/astro-components] The most important thing to know about Astro components is that they **don’t render on the client**.
[src:astro/astro-components] They render to HTML either at build-time or on-demand.
[src:astro/astro-components] You can include JavaScript code inside of your component frontmatter, and all of it will be stripped from the final page sent to your users’ browsers.
[src:astro/astro-components] The result is a faster site, with zero JavaScript footprint added by default.
[src:astro/astro-components] When your Astro component does need client-side interactivity, you can add standard HTML `<script>` tags or UI Framework components as “client islands”.
[src:astro/astro-components] For components that need to render personalized or dynamic content, you can defer their server rendering by adding a server directive.
[src:astro/astro-components] These “server islands” will render their content when it is available, without delaying the entire page load.
[src:astro/astro-components] An Astro component is made up of two main parts: the **Component Script** and the **Component Template**.
[src:astro/astro-components] Each part performs a different job, but together they provide a framework that is both easy to use and expressive enough to handle whatever you might want to build.
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro uses a code fence (`---`) to identify the component script in your Astro component.
[src:astro/astro-components] If you’ve ever written Markdown before, you may already be familiar with a similar concept called *frontmatter.* Astro’s idea of a component script was directly inspired by this concept.
[src:astro/astro-components] You can use the component script to write any JavaScript code that you need to render your template.
[src:astro/astro-components] The code fence is designed to guarantee that the JavaScript that you write in it is “fenced in.” It won’t escape into your frontend application, or fall into your user’s hands.
[src:astro/astro-components] You can safely write code here that is expensive or sensitive (like a call to your private database) without worrying about it ever ending up in your user’s browser.
[src:astro/astro-components] The component template is below the code fence and determines the HTML output of your component.
[src:astro/astro-components] If you write plain HTML here, your component will render that HTML in any Astro page it is imported and used.
[src:astro/astro-components] However, Astro’s component template syntax also supports **JavaScript expressions**, Astro `<style>` and `<script>` tags, **imported components**, and **special Astro directives**.
[src:astro/astro-components] Data and values defined in the component script can be used in the component template to produce dynamically-created HTML.
[src:astro/astro-components] Components are designed to be **reusable** and **composable**.
[src:astro/astro-components] You can use components inside of other components to build more and more advanced UI.
[src:astro/astro-components] An Astro component can define and accept props.
[src:astro/astro-components] These props then become available to the component template for rendering HTML.
[src:astro/astro-components] Props are available on the `Astro.props` global in your frontmatter script.
[src:astro/astro-components] Here is an example of a component that receives a `greeting` prop and a `name` prop.
[src:astro/astro-components] Notice that the props to be received are destructured from the global `Astro.props` object.
[src:astro/astro-components] You can also define your props with TypeScript with a `Props` type interface.
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro will automatically pick up the `Props` interface in your frontmatter and give type warnings/errors.
[src:astro/astro-components] These props can also be given default values when destructured from `Astro.props`.
[src:astro/astro-components] Component props can be given default values to use when none are provided.
[src:astro/astro-components] The `<slot />` element is a placeholder for external HTML content, allowing you to inject (or “slot”) child elements from other files into your component template.
[src:astro/astro-components] By default, all child elements passed to a component will be rendered in its `<slot />`.
[src:astro/astro-components] This pattern is the basis of an Astro layout component: an entire page of HTML content can be “wrapped” with `<SomeLayoutComponent></SomeLayoutComponent>` tags and sent to the component to render inside of common page elements defined there.
[src:astro/astro-components] for more ways to access and render slot content.
[src:astro/astro-components] An Astro component can also have named slots.
[src:astro/astro-components] This allows you to pass only HTML elements with the corresponding slot name into a slot’s location.
[src:astro/astro-components] To inject HTML content into a particular slot, use the `slot` attribute on any child element to specify the name of the slot.
[src:astro/astro-components] All other child elements of the component will be injected into the default (unnamed) `<slot />`.
[src:astro/astro-components] Inject multiple rows and columns of HTML content using a `slot=""` attribute to specify the `"header"` and `"body"` content.
[src:astro/astro-components] Note that named slots must be an immediate child of the component.
[src:astro/astro-components] You cannot pass named slots through nested elements.
[src:astro/astro-components] Slots can also render **fallback content**.
[src:astro/astro-components] When there are no matching children passed to a slot, a `<slot />` element will render its own placeholder children.
[src:astro/astro-components] Fallback content will only be displayed when there are no matching elements with the `slot="name"` attribute being passed in to a named slot.
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro will pass an empty slot when a slot element exists but has no content to pass.
[src:astro/astro-components] Fallback content cannot be used as a default when an empty slot is passed.
[src:astro/astro-components] Fallback content is only displayed when no slot element can be found.
[src:astro/astro-components] Slots can be transferred to other components.
[src:astro/astro-components] Now, the default and `head` slots passed to `HomeLayout` will be transferred to the `BaseLayout` parent.
[src:astro/astro-components] Astro supports importing and using `.html` files as components or placing these files within the `src/pages/` subdirectory as pages.
[src:astro/astro-components] You may want to use HTML components if you’re reusing code from an existing site built without a framework, or if you want to ensure that your component has no dynamic features.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This avoids the monolithic JavaScript payloads that slow down the responsiveness of many other, modern JavaScript web frameworks.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] The term “component island” was first coined by Etsy’s frontend architect Katie Sylor-Miller in 2019.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This idea was then expanded on and documented in this post by Preact creator Jason Miller on August 11, 2020.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] In contrast, most JavaScript-based web frameworks hydrate & render an entire website as one large JavaScript application (also known as a single-page application, or SPA).
[src:astro/concepts-islands] SPAs provide simplicity and power but suffer from page-load performance problems due to heavy client-side JavaScript usage.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] SPAs have their place, even embedded inside an Astro page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] But, SPAs lack the native ability to selectively and strategically hydrate, making them a heavy-handed choice for most projects on the web today.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Astro became popular as the first mainstream JavaScript web framework with selective hydration built-in, using that same component islands pattern first coined by Sylor-Miller.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] We’ve since expanded and evolved on Sylor-Miller’s original work, which helped to inspire a similar component island approach to dynamically server-rendered content.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] In Astro, an island is an enhanced UI component on an otherwise static page of HTML.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] A **client island** is an interactive JavaScript UI component that is hydrated separately from the rest of the page, while a **server island** is a UI component that server-renders its dynamic content separately from the rest of the page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Both islands run expensive or slower processes independently, on a per-component basis, for optimized page loads.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Astro components are the building blocks of your page template.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] They render to static HTML with no client-side runtime.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Think of a client island as an interactive widget floating in a sea of otherwise static, lightweight, server-rendered HTML.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Server islands can be added for personalized or dynamic server-rendered elements, such as a logged in visitor’s profile picture.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] An island always runs in isolation from other islands on the page, and multiple islands can exist on a page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Client islands can still share state and communicate with each other, even though they run in different component contexts.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This flexibility allows Astro to support multiple UI frameworks like React, Preact, Svelte, Vue, and SolidJS.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Because they are independent, you can even mix several frameworks on each page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This may sound strict, but this behavior is what keeps Astro websites fast by default and protects developers from accidentally sending unnecessary or unwanted JavaScript that might slow down their website.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Turning any static UI component into an interactive island requires only a `client:*` directive.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Astro then automatically builds and bundles your client-side JavaScript for optimized performance.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] With islands, client-side JavaScript is only loaded for the explicit interactive components that you mark using `client:*` directives.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] And because interaction is configured at the component-level, you can handle different loading priorities for each component based on its usage.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] For example, `client:idle` tells a component to load when the browser becomes idle, and `client:visible` tells a component to load only once it enters the viewport.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] The most obvious benefit of building with Astro Islands is performance: the majority of your website is converted to fast, static HTML and JavaScript is only loaded for the individual components that need it.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] JavaScript is one of the slowest assets that you can load per-byte, so every byte counts.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] In the example illustration above, the low-priority “image carousel” island doesn’t need to block the high-priority “header” island.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] The two load in parallel and hydrate in isolation, meaning that the header becomes interactive immediately without having to wait for the heavier carousel lower down the page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Even better, you can tell Astro exactly how and when to render each component.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] If that image carousel is really expensive to load, you can attach a special client directive that tells Astro to only load the carousel when it becomes visible on the page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] If the user never sees it, it never loads.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] In Astro, it’s up to you as the developer to explicitly tell Astro which components on the page need to also run in the browser.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Astro will only hydrate exactly what’s needed on the page and leave the rest of your site as static HTML.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Server islands are a way to move expensive or slow server-side code out of the way of the main rendering process, making it easy to combine high-performance static HTML and dynamic server-generated components.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This breaks up your page with smaller areas of server-rendered content that each load in parallel.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Your page’s main content can be rendered immediately with placeholder content, such as a generic avatar, until your island’s own content is available.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] With server islands, having small components of personalized content does not delay the rendering of an otherwise static page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This rendering pattern was built to be portable.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] It does not depend on any server infrastructure so it will work with any host, from a Node.js server in a Docker container to the serverless provider of your choice.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] One benefit of server islands is the ability to render the more highly dynamic parts of your page on the fly.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] This allows the outer shell and main content to be more aggressively cached, providing faster performance.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Another benefit is providing a great visitor experience.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Server islands are optimized and load quickly, often even before the browser has even painted the page.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] But in the short time it takes for your islands to render, you can display custom fallback content and prevent any layout shift.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] An example of a site that benefits from Astro’s server islands is an e-commerce storefront.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Using server islands for these elements, your visitor will see the most important part of the page, your product, immediately.
[src:astro/concepts-islands] Generic avatars, loading spinners, and store announcements can be displayed as fallback content until the personalized parts are available.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Here are five core design principles to help explain why we built Astro, the problems that it exists to solve, and why Astro may be the best choice for your project or team.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] **Server-first:** Websites run faster when they render HTML on the server.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] **Fast by default:** It should be impossible to build a slow website in Astro.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] **Easy to use:** You don’t need to be an expert to build something with Astro.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] **Developer-focused:** You should have the resources you need to be successful.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] By contrast, most modern web frameworks were designed for building *web applications*.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] These frameworks excel at building more complex, application-like experiences in the browser: logged-in admin dashboards, inboxes, social networks, todo lists, and even native-like applications like Figma and Ping.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] However with that complexity, they can struggle to provide great performance when delivering your content.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro’s focus on content from its beginnings as a static site builder have allowed Astro to **sensibly scale up to performant, powerful, dynamic web applications** that still respect your content and your audience.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro’s unique focus on content lets Astro make tradeoffs and deliver unmatched performance features that wouldn’t make sense for more application-focused web frameworks to implement.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] This approach stands in contrast to other modern JavaScript web frameworks like Next.js, SvelteKit, Nuxt, Remix, and others.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] These frameworks were built for client-side rendering of your entire website and include server-side rendering mainly to address performance concerns.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] This approach has been dubbed the **Single-Page App (SPA)**, in contrast with Astro’s **Multi-Page App (MPA)** approach.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] However, these come at the expense of additional complexity and performance tradeoffs.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] These tradeoffs harm page performance -- critical metrics like Time to Interactive (TTI) -- which doesn’t make much sense for content-focused websites where first-load performance is essential.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro’s server-first approach allows you to opt in to client-side rendering only if, and exactly as, necessary.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] You can choose to add UI framework components that run on the client.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] You can take advantage of Astro’s view transitions router for finer control over select page transitions and animations.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro’s server-first rendering, either pre-rendered or on-demand, provides performant defaults that you can enhance and extend.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Good performance is always important, but it is *especially* critical for websites whose success depends on displaying your content.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] It has been well-proven that poor performance loses you engagement, conversions, and money.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] In many web frameworks, it is easy to build a website that looks great during development only to load painfully slow once deployed.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] JavaScript is often the culprit, since many phones and lower-powered devices rarely match the speed of a developer’s laptop.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro’s magic is in how it combines the two values explained above -- a content focus with a server-first architecture -- to make tradeoffs and deliver features that other frameworks cannot.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] The result is amazing web performance for every website, out of the box.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] An Astro website can load 40% faster with 90% less JavaScript than the same site built with the most popular React web framework.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] But don’t take our word for it: watch Astro’s performance leave Ryan Carniato (creator of Solid.js and Marko) speechless.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] The `.astro` UI language is a superset of HTML: any valid HTML is valid Astro templating syntax!
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] So, if you can write HTML, you can write Astro components!
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] But, it also combines some of our favorite features borrowed from other component languages like JSX expressions (React) and CSS scoping by default (Svelte and Vue).
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] This closeness to HTML also makes it easier to use progressive enhancement and common accessibility patterns without any overhead.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] We then made sure that you could also use your favorite UI component languages that you already know, and even reuse components you might already have.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] React, Preact, Svelte, Vue, Solid, and others, including web components, are all supported for authoring UI components in an Astro project.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro was designed to be less complex than other UI frameworks and languages.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] One big reason for this is that Astro was designed to render on the server, not in the browser.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] That means that you don’t need to worry about hooks (React), stale closures (also React), refs (Vue), observables (Svelte), atoms, selectors, reactions, or derivations.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] There is no reactivity on the server, so all of that complexity melts away.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] One of our favorite sayings is **opt in to complexity.** We designed Astro to remove as much “required complexity” as possible from the developer experience, especially as you onboard for the first time.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] You can build a “Hello World” example website in Astro with just HTML and CSS.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Then, when you need to build something more powerful, you can incrementally reach for new features and APIs as you go.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] We strongly believe that Astro is only a successful project if people love using it.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro has everything you need to support you as you build with Astro.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Astro invests in developer tools like a great CLI experience from the moment you open your terminal, an official VS Code extension for syntax highlighting, TypeScript and Intellisense, and documentation actively maintained by hundreds of community contributors and available in 14 languages.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Our welcoming, respectful, inclusive community on Discord is ready to provide support, motivation, and encouragement.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Open a `#support` thread to get help with your project.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Visit our dedicated `#showcase` channel for sharing your Astro sites, blog posts, videos, and even work-in-progress for safe feedback and constructive criticism.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] Participate in regular live events such as our weekly community call, “Talking and Doc’ing,” and API/bug bashes.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] As an open-source project, we welcome contributions of all types and sizes from community members of all experience levels.
[src:astro/concepts-why-astro] You are invited to join in roadmap discussions to shape the future of Astro, and we hope you’ll contribute fixes and features to the core codebase, compiler, docs, language tools, websites, and other projects.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting is often used to provide a customized interface for the user.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] These scripts may assemble client characteristics for use in customizing the response based on those characteristics, the user's requirements, access rights, etc.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting also enables the website owner to hide the source code that generates the interface, whereas, with client-side scripting, the user has access to all the code received by the client.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] A downside to the use of server-side scripting is that the client needs to make further requests over the network to the server in order to show new information to the user via the web browser.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] These requests can slow down the experience for the user, place more load on the server, and prevent the use of the application when the user is disconnected from the server.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] When the server serves data in a commonly used manner, for example, according to the HTTP or FTP protocols, users may have their choice of a number of client programs (most modern web browsers can request and receive data using both of those protocols).
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] In the case of more specialized applications, programmers may write their own server, client, and communications protocol, that can only be used with one another.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Programs that run on a user's local computer without ever sending or receiving data over a network are not considered clients, and so the operations of such programs would not be considered client-side operations.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Netscape introduced an implementation of JavaScript for server-side scripting with Netscape Enterprise Server, first released in December, 1994 (soon after releasing JavaScript for browsers).
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripting was later used in early 1996 by Fred Dufresne while developing the first website for Boston, MA television station WCVB.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] The technology is described in US patent 5835712 Archived 2020-02-25 at the Wayback Machine.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] The patent was issued in 1998 and is now owned by Open Invention Network (OIN).
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] In 2010, OIN named Fred DuFresne a "Distinguished Inventor" for his work on server-side scripting.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] In the earlier days of the web, server-side scripting was almost exclusively performed by using a combination of C programs, Perl scripts, and shell scripts using the Common Gateway Interface (CGI).
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Those scripts were executed by the operating system, and the results were served back by the web server.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Many modern web servers can directly execute on-line scripting languages such as ASP, JSP, Perl, PHP and Ruby either by the web server itself or via extension modules (e.g. mod_perl or mod_php) to the webserver.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] For example, WebDNA includes its own embedded database system.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Either form of scripting (i.e., CGI or direct execution) can be used to build up complex multi-page sites, but direct execution usually results in less overhead because of the lower number of calls to external interpreters.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Dynamic websites sometimes use custom web application servers, such as Glassfish, Plack and Python's "Base HTTP Server" library, although some may not consider this to be server-side scripting.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] When using dynamic web-based scripting techniques, developers must have a keen understanding of the logical, temporal, and physical separation between the client and the server.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] For a user's action to trigger the execution of server-side code, for example, a developer working with classic ASP must explicitly cause the user's browser to make a request back to the webserver.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Server-side scripts are completely processed by the servers instead of clients.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] When clients request a page containing server-side scripts, the application server processes the scripts and returns an HTML page to the client.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] With the advent of single-page applications, an updated approach to server-side scripting was introduced, known as server-side rendering.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, static HTML can be sent from the server to the client, and client-side JavaScript then makes the web page dynamic by attaching event handlers to the HTML elements in a process called hydration.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Examples of frameworks that support server-side rendering are Next.js, Nuxt.js, Angular.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] An alternative to server-side rendering is static site generation.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] With server-side rendering, the page is generally assembled on the server once per each request.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] By contrast, with static site generation, the application generates all the static HTML pages at build time.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] These pre-built pages are then sent to the client at each request, without having to build them again.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] This leads to faster rendering times, since a new page doesn't have to be generated on every request; the server simply hands over a file it already generated in the past.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] The downside is that when some data on the page changes, it needs to be rebuilt.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Examples of static site generation tools are Jekyll and Gatsby.
[src:astro/server-side-rendering] Sites generated by static site generation tools are often hosted on Netlify, Vercel or GitHub pages.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] SSGs typically consist of a template written in HTML with a templating system, such as Liquid (Jekyll) or Go template (Hugo).
[src:astro/static-site-generator] The same structure (typically a Git repository) includes content in a plain-text format such as Markdown or reStructuredText, or in a structural meta format such as JSON or XML.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] A single plain-text file may correspond to a single web page.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Alternatively, a single structural metadata file may correspond to an entire website if a single-page application framework like AngularJS is used.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] The website variable settings are stored in a plaintext configuration file `_config.yml` (YAML), `_config.toml` (TOML) or `_config.json` (JSON).
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Page files typically also start with a YAML, TOML, or JSON preamble to define variables such as title, permalink, or date.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Files with names that begin with an underscore (`_`) such as `_index.md` (as opposed to `index.md`) are considered templates or archetypes and are thus not rendered as pages themselves.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Several hundred SSGs have been documented to exist, with the vast majority being written in languages that are already prominent on the web, such as Python, Go, JavaScript and TypeScript.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Many *server-side template systems* have the option to publish output pages on the server, where the published pages are static.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] This is common on content management systems, like Vignette, but is not considered out-server generation.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] In the majority of cases, this "publish option" doesn't interfere with the *template system*, and it can be made by external software, as Wget.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] People began to use server-side dynamic pages generated from templates with pre-existing software adapted for this task.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] This early software was the preprocessors and macro languages, adapted for web use, running on CGI.
[src:astro/static-site-generator] Next, a simple but relevant technology was the direct execution made on extension modules, starting with SSI.
[src:astro/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:astro/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:astro/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:astro/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:astro/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:astro/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:astro/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:astro/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:astro/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:astro/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:astro/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:astro/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:astro/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:astro/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:astro/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:astro/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:astro/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:astro/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:astro/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:astro/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:astro/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:astro/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:astro/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:astro/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:astro/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:astro/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:astro/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:astro/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:astro/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:astro/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:astro/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:astro/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:astro/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:astro/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:astro/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:astro/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:astro/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:astro/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:astro/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:astro/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:astro/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:astro/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:astro/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:astro/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:astro/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:astro/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:astro/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:astro/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:astro/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:astro/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:astro/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:astro/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:astro/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:astro/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:astro/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:astro/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:astro/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:astro/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:astro/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:astro/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:astro/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:astro/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:astro/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:astro/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:astro/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:astro/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:astro/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:astro/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:astro/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:astro/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:astro/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:astro/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:astro/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:astro/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:astro/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:astro/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:astro/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:astro/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
